      "Supports": "Duodenal thickening, abdominal pain, fever, and potential for fistula formation.",
      "Arguments Against": "Acute presentation with septicemia (Streptococcus anginosus) and renal vein thrombosis are atypical for initial presentation of Crohn's disease.",
      "Support": "Weakly supported"
    },
    "Infective endocarditis with septic pulmonary emboli": {
      "Supports": "Fever, bacteremia (Streptococcus anginosus), and pulmonary opacities.",
